            "content": "Before writing code, read design.md D1 + spec.md's \"Concurrent move and child-creation cannot produce a stale path\" scenario, then had advisor independently verify a concern. Confirmed real, flagging per your \"stop and report on genuine design contradictions\" instruction.\n\n**The gap:** D1 says move() locks the subtree root FOR UPDATE; createChild() locks its immediate parent FOR UPDATE. Those only contend on the SAME row when the child's parent IS the exact unit being moved. If the child is created under a strict descendant of the moved subtree (not the root itself — which spec.md's \"a unit in that subtree\" phrasing covers), the two operations lock different rows and never serialize.\n\nUnder READ COMMITTED, a plain UPDATE's candidate set is fixed by its statement-start snapshot; blocking mid-scan on a lock only triggers a re-check (EvalPlanQual) for rows already in that set, never for brand-new rows committed by someone else afterward. So: createChild locks descendant X, reads its old path, inserts a child, commits — all while move() is still in flight rewriting the subtree via a different row lock. move()'s own deferred UPDATE never sees the new child row (it postdates its snapshot), so its bulk rewrite skips it. The deferred constraint trigger doesn't catch it either: at createChild's own commit, the parent's path (as far as that transaction can see) is still pre-move and consistent; move() never touches the child row so no trigger fires for it there either. Net result: silent, permanent path/parent inconsistency, with neither serialization nor an abort — the spec's own two required outcomes.\n\n**Fix that stays inside a row-lock primitive:** lock the TREE ROOT (first path segment, one shared row per tree) FOR UPDATE, and lock-BEFORE-read (acquire the lock, then read the path you derive from, not the other way — I found `move()` also has a related staleness bug: it currently computes `oldPrefix` from the caller-supplied `unit.path`